22. Secondly, we say, as before, tha-t punishment, in one sense, does not imply fault, but is opposed to fault. See Sect. 11.

23. Thirdly, we say that the Law obliges under fault, but obliges conditionally only. The whole Law is to be taken together; the ordination, the condition, and the combination of the two. A man is culpable who neither conforms to the ordination, nor submits to the condition. See Sect. 19.
